THE BLADES QUESTLINE
A Campaign-Long Story Arc
Note: This questline is triggered by the party's actions at the White River Bridge checkpoint. If they betray Delphine to the Thalmor, this sequence begins. If they do not betray her, Delphine contacts them instead and this plays out very differently.

PHASE 1: THE AFTERMATH
Timing: Immediately after crossing the checkpoint
 Duration: 2-3 in-game days
THE RAID ON RIVERWOOD
If the party informed the Thalmor about Delphine and the Sleeping Giant Inn, Rulindil takes immediate action.
Day 1 (Morning After Checkpoint):
Rulindil sends a coded message to the Thalmor Embassy: "Potential Blade operative identified in Riverwood. Request authorization for immediate action."
The Embassy responds within hours: "Authorized. Capture alive if possible. Delphine is a priority target."
Day 2 (Evening):
A Thalmor strike team (8 Justiciars, 2 Wizards, led by Rulindil himself) arrives in Riverwood
They surround the Sleeping Giant Inn at midnight
Delphine fights but is overwhelmed (she kills two Justiciars before being subdued with Paralyze)
She's taken to the Thalmor Embassy in chains
Day 3 (Rumors Spread):
Word reaches Riften through travelers: "The Thalmor raided Riverwood. Arrested someone at the inn. People are scared."
Merchants whisper: "They took a woman. Blonde, forties. She fought like a soldier."
ESBERN'S RESPONSE
Esbern's Dead Drop System: Delphine and Esbern have a coded communication system:
Every three days, Delphine leaves a chalk mark on a specific wall in Riften (near the marketplace)
The mark means: "All clear, no contact needed"
No mark means: "Emergency, investigate"
Day 3 (Delphine Misses Check-In):
Esbern visits the dead drop location in Riften
No mark. He waits. Still nothing.
He begins investigation: talks to beggars, informants, traveling merchants
Within a day, he hears about the Riverwood raid
Day 4-5 (Esbern Investigates):
He sends a trusted beggar to Riverwood to gather details
The beggar returns: "Thalmor. Eight soldiers. They took a woman from the inn. The innkeeper said she was 'just a barmaid,' but nobody believes it."
Esbern knows. Delphine is captured or dead.
Day 6 (Esbern's Decision):
"I am alone. The last Blade. Delphine is gone. The dragons return. There is no Dragonborn. I must find another way."
He begins monitoring for dragon sightings, waiting for news of dragon-slayers.

PHASE 2: THE DRAGON-KILLERS
Timing: After the party kills Sahloknir at Kynesgrove
 Duration: 1-2 sessions
NEWS SPREADS
Immediate Aftermath (Hours After Kynesgrove):
Survivors flee to nearby settlements
Word spreads: "A dragon attacked Kynesgrove. The village is destroyed. But... someone killed it. Mercenaries. Warriors. They say the dragon's body burned away to nothing."
Day 1-2 (Rumors Reach Cities):
Merchants carry the story to Windhelm, Riften, Whiterun
The details are garbled: "Five warriors." "They had a giant with them." "One of them drank the dragon's blood."
But the core fact remains: A dragon was killed. By mortals.
Day 3 (Esbern Hears): Esbern's network of informants brings him the news. A beggar approaches him in the Ratway:
Beggar: "You wanted to know about dragons, yeah? There was one. Kynesgrove. Big one. Came out of the ground, they say. Alduin himself raised it from a burial mound."
Esbern: "And?"
Beggar: "And some group killed it. Wardens, they're calling themselves. The King's new agents or something. Four of them, maybe five. Got a Nord with them who's... wrong somehow. People say his blood boils."
Esbern's Reaction: He cross-references this with everything he knows:
The timing (right after a checkpoint incident)
The description (matches reports from Riverwood of armed travelers)
The fact they killed a dragon
He makes a decision: "They're all I have."

THE CONTACT
Esbern's Method: He doesn't approach directly. He's too paranoid. Instead:
Step 1: Observation (Day 4-5)
Esbern uses his network to track the party's movements
Where are they staying? Who are they talking to?
He watches them from a distance (high Guile, master of stealth)
He confirms: They're real. They're capable. They killed a dragon.
Step 2: The Intermediary (Day 6)
Esbern contacts a trusted courier (a beggar named Snilf)
He gives Snilf a sealed letter and 20 gold
"Deliver this to the Wardens. Do not tell them who sent you. If they ask, say only: 'A friend who knows what's coming.'"
The Letter: When the party receives this, it's written in careful, scholarly handwriting on old parchment:
To the Wardens who slew the dragon at Kynesgrove,
You have done what few mortals can claim: you have killed a dragon. Not just any dragonΓÇöSahloknir, lieutenant of Alduin the World-Eater, raised from death by the Black Dragon himself.
You know, then, what I know: the dragons return. Alduin rises. The end of the world approaches.
The prophecy speaks of a Dragonborn who will stand against this darkness. I have searched for thirty years. I have found nothing. No Dragonborn walks Skyrim.
Which means we face the apocalypse alone.
I can help you. I have knowledgeΓÇöof dragons, their lairs, their weaknesses. I have weapons from the Dragon War. I know where to find the answers we need to stop Alduin permanently.
But I cannot do this alone. I need dragon-slayers. I need you.
If you are willing, come to Riften. The Ratway, in the Warrens. Ask for "the old scholar." Come soon. Time is not our ally.
ΓÇöA Friend
GM Notes:
The party can choose to follow up or ignore this
If they ignore it, Esbern will send increasingly desperate messages
If they ask around Riften about "the old scholar," everyone knows: "Oh, the crazy old man in the Ratway. Talks about dragons and the end times. Harmless, mostly."

THE MEETING
Location: The Ratway Warrens, Riften
 Setup: A maze of tunnels beneath Riften, filled with beggars, criminals, and Skooma addicts
When the party descends into the Ratway looking for Esbern:
The Approach:
They must navigate through the Ratway (potential encounters with thugs, beggars)
Eventually they reach the WarrensΓÇöa section of collapsed tunnels converted into makeshift rooms
One door is marked with a chalk symbol (a dragon's head, very faint)
The Door: If they knock, a voice from inside (old, suspicious):
Esbern: "Who sent you?"
The party must answer correctly (mention the letter, the dragon, etc.) or Esbern won't open the door.
Inside:
READ ALOUD:
"The door opens a crack, held by a chain. An old man's face appearsΓÇöweathered, gaunt, with sharp gray eyes that miss nothing. He looks you over, one by one, his gaze lingering on weapons, armor, scars.
After a long moment, he removes the chain and steps back.
The room is small, cramped, and chaotic. Every surface is covered with books, scrolls, maps. The walls are plastered with sketches of dragons, ancient Nordic runes, and what appears to be a timeline of historical events. A single candle provides light.
The old man closes the door behind you and locks it. Three times.
'I am Esbern,' he says quietly. 'Last of the Blades. And you... you killed Sahloknir.'"

THE PITCH
Esbern's Opening: He doesn't waste time with pleasantries. He's desperate and shows it.
Esbern: "I'll be direct. The dragons are returning. AlduinΓÇöthe World-Eater, the dragon who devoured the last worldΓÇöhas returned. He's raising his lieutenants from their graves. Sahloknir was the first. There will be more."
(He gestures to the timeline on the wall)
Esbern: "The prophecy of the Dragonborn is clear. When Alduin returns, a Dragonborn will rise to stop him. A mortal with the soul of a dragon, able to speak the Thu'um and devour dragon souls."
(His voice becomes bitter)
Esbern: "I've searched for thirty years. DelphineΓÇömy partner, my friendΓÇösearched even longer. We found nothing. No Dragonborn. No hero. No salvation."
(He looks at each of them)
Esbern: "But you killed a dragon. You did what the prophecy says only a Dragonborn can do. How?"
Let the party explain Kynesgrove.
Esbern's Response: After hearing their story:
Esbern: "Tactics. Preparation. Desperation. No divine gift. No dragon soul. Just... mortals, fighting for survival."
(He smiles, but it's sad)
Esbern: "Then that's what we have. Mortals. No prophecy. No chosen one. Just people who refuse to lie down and die."

THE OFFER
Esbern: "I need your help. And you need mine. Here's what I can offer:
Knowledge: I've spent forty years studying dragons. I know their weaknesses. Where they nest. How they hunt. How they think.
Weapons: I know the location of Sky Haven Temple, the last Blades sanctuary. Inside are weapons and armor from the Dragon WarΓÇöDragonbane, Blades Armor, equipment specifically designed to fight dragons.
A Plan: I know how the ancient Nords defeated Alduin the first time. It wasn't prophecy. It was knowledge, courage, and a willingness to do what was necessary. We can follow that path.
A Purpose: You've killed one dragon. If you walk away now, you'll spend the rest of your short lives running from the rest. But if you help me... we can end this. We can kill Alduin. We can save Skyrim."
(He pauses)
Esbern: "I won't lie to you. This will be dangerous. You might die. Probably will die. But you'll die as dragon-slayers. As heroes. As the people who stood when the world needed them."
(He extends his hand)
Esbern: "Will you help me?"

QUESTIONS & ANSWERS
The party will likely have questions. Here are Esbern's responses:
"What happened to the other Blades?"
"Dead. Slaughtered during the Great War by the Thalmor. The White-Gold Concordat made us illegalΓÇöenemies of the Empire we'd served for millennia. We were hunted. Most died fighting. Some fled. I hid. Delphine hid. And now... Delphine is gone too."
"Gone how?"
(Esbern hesitates, pain crossing his face) "She was in Riverwood. Gathering intelligence. She... stopped checking in. I investigated. The Thalmor raided the Sleeping Giant Inn three days ago. Took someone matching her description. Either she's captured, or she's dead."
"Can we rescue her?"
(Esbern looks at them with sudden, desperate hope) "You'd do that? You'd risk infiltrating the Thalmor Embassy for someone you've never met?"
(If yes:) "Then... yes. Yes, we can try. She's being held at the Embassy north of Solitude. It's a fortress, but if we can get you insideΓÇödisguised, perhaps, during one of their partiesΓÇöyou might be able to reach the dungeon. She knows their security. Their routines. With her help, we'd have a real chance."
(If no:) "I understand. It's a suicide mission. I... I just hoped..." (He composes himself) "Then we continue without her. She'd want us to. The mission is bigger than any one Blade."
"Why should we trust you?"
"You shouldn't. I'm a stranger hiding in a sewer, talking about the end of the world. For all you know, I'm mad."
(He gestures to the walls)
"But everything I've predicted has come true. I said Alduin would return. He did. I said he'd raise dragons from their graves. Sahloknir rose. I said there'd be no Dragonborn to save us. And where is he?"
(He meets their eyes)
"You don't have to trust me. But you killed a dragon. You know what's coming. And I'm offering you the tools to fight it. What else will you do? Wait for the next dragon to find you unprepared?"
"What do you get out of this?"
"A chance to fulfill my oath. The Blades exist to protect the people of Tamriel from the greatest threats. There is no greater threat than Alduin. If I die stopping him, I die with purpose. If I fail... well. We all die anyway."

ACCEPTING THE QUEST
If the party agrees to help:
Esbern: (visible relief) "Thank you. Truly. You've given me something I'd lostΓÇöhope."
(He moves to a table and unrolls a map)
Esbern: "Here's what we do first. Before we can face Alduin, we need to understand what we're fighting. That means finding Sky Haven Temple. It's hidden in the Reach, in the Karthspire. The temple holds Alduin's WallΓÇöa complete record of the Dragon War, carved by Akaviri Blades three thousand years ago. It will tell us how the ancient Nords defeated Alduin the first time."
(He marks the location)
Esbern: "But first... if you're willing to risk it... Delphine. The Embassy. We need her. I need her."
(He looks at them)
Esbern: "Where do you want to start?"

PHASE 3: DIPLOMATIC IMMUNITY (OPTIONAL)
Timing: After recruiting Esbern, before Sky Haven Temple
 Duration: 1 session
 Prerequisite: Party agrees to rescue Delphine
THE PLAN
Esbern's Intelligence: "The Thalmor Embassy holds parties regularlyΓÇödiplomatic receptions, meetings with Imperial officials, cultural events. It's how they maintain their image of civility while running a torture dungeon beneath. If we can get you an invitation to one of these parties, you can infiltrate during the chaos."
The Contact: Esbern knows a Wood Elf named Malborn who works at the Embassy as a servant. Malborn hates the Thalmor (they killed his family during the Great War) and has been feeding information to the Blades for years.
The Meeting: Esbern arranges a meeting with Malborn at the Winking Skeever in Solitude (ironic, given what the party did to Delphine).
Malborn: "You want to break into the Embassy? You're insane. But... if you're serious, I can help. There's a party in three days. Ambassador Elenwen is hosting Imperial dignitaries. Security will be tight, but during the party itself, there'll be distractions."
The Requirements:
An Invitation: Malborn can forge one, but the party needs a cover story (merchants, scholars, minor nobles, etc.)
Party Clothes: No armor allowed at the party. The party must acquire formal clothing.
Smuggled Gear: Malborn can smuggle weapons/armor into the Embassy ahead of time, hidden in the basement near the dungeon.

THE INFILTRATION
Structure: This is a stealth/social mission with an action climax.
PART 1: THE PARTY (Social/Stealth)
The Setting: The Embassy is filled with Thalmor officials, Imperial dignitaries, and wealthy merchants. Music, wine, conversation.
Objective:
Mingle and maintain cover (Guile checks to seem legitimate)
Find Malborn and get the key to the basement
Slip away from the party without being noticed
Key NPCs:
Elenwen: The Ambassador. Sharp, suspicious, and charming. She'll engage the party in conversation to assess them.
Rulindil: If he's still alive after the checkpoint encounter, he's here. He might recognize the party.
Malborn: Serving drinks. He'll slip the party the key and directions when safe.
Complications:
If Rulindil is present and recognizes them, he'll become suspicious
Elenwen may ask probing questions about their "business" in Skyrim
Random Thalmor guests may engage them in conversation, testing their cover story
PART 2: THE DUNGEON (Stealth/Combat)
The Descent:
Once the party has the key, they slip away to the basement
Malborn has hidden their gear in a chest near the kitchen
From there, they must navigate to the dungeon
The Dungeon: A small, grim series of cells beneath the Embassy.
Guards:
2x Thalmor Justiciars on patrol
1x Thalmor Torturer (in the interrogation room)
Delphine's Cell: She's in the furthest cell, weak but alive. When they find her:
Delphine: (weakly) "Who... sent you?"
If they mention Esbern:
"Esbern? He's alive? Thank the Divines. I thought... I thought I was the last."
If they reveal they betrayed her at Riverwood:
(Her expression hardens) "You. You told them about me. You sold me to the Thalmor."
(She grabs the cell bars, fury and pain in her eyes)
"Why are you here? To finish the job? To watch me hang?"
The party must convince her:
Guile Check (Very Hard, -6): Convince her they regret it, that Esbern sent them, that they need her
Alternative: Esbern sent a token (a Blades medallion) that proves they're legitimate
If convinced:
(Delphine takes a shaky breath) "Fine. Get me out of here. But know thisΓÇöI don't trust you. I don't forgive you. But Esbern needs help, and I need to get out of this cell. We'll settle our debts later."
PART 3: THE ESCAPE (Combat)
The Alarm: Freeing Delphine triggers an alarm (magical ward on her cell, or a guard discovers the unconscious torturers).
The Response:
4x Thalmor Justiciars converge on the dungeon
2x Thalmor Wizards cut off escape routes
The party must fight their way out
Delphine's Contribution: Even weakened, she's a trained Blade. She'll grab a weapon from a fallen guard and fight alongside the party (though she's at half HP and has Disadvantage on all rolls due to torture/starvation).
The Route: Malborn opens a back exitΓÇöa smuggler's tunnel that leads out of the Embassy grounds. The party must reach it before being overwhelmed.
Success: They escape into the wilderness. The Thalmor will be hunting them, but they're free.

THE AFTERMATH
Delphine's State: She's physically injured and emotionally scarred. She needs rest, healing, and time.
The Reunion: When they bring her to Esbern in the Ratway:
READ ALOUD:
"Esbern opens the door and freezes. For a long moment, he just stares at DelphineΓÇöbruised, limping, but alive.
Then he steps forward and embraces her. No words. Just two old soldiers who thought they'd lost everything, holding onto the last friend they have left.
When they finally pull apart, Delphine wipes her eyes.
'I thought you were dead,' Esbern says quietly.
'I thought you were too,' Delphine replies. 'Guess we're both too stubborn to die.'
She turns to look at the party, and there's something hard in her eyes.
'Esbern says you're helping. That you killed a dragon. That you're... all we have.'
(She crosses her arms)
'I don't trust you. But I trust Esbern. And if he believes you can help stop Alduin, then I'll work with you. For now.'"
Moving Forward:
Delphine needs a few days to recover (mechanical rest, healing)
After she's stable, she and Esbern will both guide the party to Sky Haven Temple
Delphine is cold toward the party but professionalΓÇöshe won't let personal grudges stop the mission
If Delphine Was Not Rescued:
Esbern is deeply saddened but continues
He becomes more desperate, more willing to make moral compromises
The party proceeds to Sky Haven with just Esbern

PHASE 4: SKY HAVEN TEMPLE
Timing: After meeting Esbern (and optionally rescuing Delphine)
 Duration: 1 session
THE JOURNEY
Location: The Reach, near Karthspire
 Travel Time: 3-4 days from Riften
Esbern's Explanation (During Travel):
"Sky Haven Temple was built by the Akaviri Blades during the First Era, long before the Septim Empire. It was meant to be a sanctuaryΓÇöa place to train dragon-slayers and preserve knowledge of the Dragon War. When the dragons were thought extinct, it was sealed and forgotten. Only a handful of Blades even knew it existed."
"Inside is Alduin's WallΓÇöa complete historical record of the Dragon War, carved in stone. Every battle. Every victory. Every sacrifice. And most importantly... how the ancient Nords defeated Alduin the first time."
Delphine's Addition (If Present):
"We've never been inside. The temple requires the blood of a Dragonborn to open. We've been searching for a Dragonborn for decades, hoping to bring them here. Now..."
(She looks at Esbern)
"Now we're improvising."

KARTHSPIRE
The Exterior: A massive stone structure carved into a mountain, partially collapsed and overgrown. The entrance is a bridge across a chasm, guarded by a puzzle door.
The Forsworn: The area around Karthspire has been claimed by Forsworn (Reachmen rebels). They've set up camp near the temple entrance.
Options:
Stealth: Sneak past the Forsworn (Agility checks)
Combat: Fight through them (4-6 Forsworn warriors)
Diplomacy: Convince them you're not their enemy (Very Hard Guile checkΓÇöthey hate outsiders)
Esbern's Preference:
"We don't have time for a war. Sneak if you can. Fight if you must. But get us to that door."

THE BLOOD SEAL
The Door: A massive stone door carved with Akaviri symbols and a dragon's head. In the center is a hand-shaped indentation.
The Inscription (in Akaviri, translated by Esbern):
"Dragonblood shall seal and Dragonblood shall open. Only the chosen may enter."
The Problem: The seal requires the blood of a Dragonborn. There is no Dragonborn.
Esbern's Solution: He's been researching this for years. He has a theory.
Esbern: "The seal was designed to respond to dragon blood carried in mortal veins. But what if we bypass the 'mortal' part? You killed Sahloknir. His body burned away, but dragons leave tracesΓÇöscales, bones, ichor. Did any of you collect anything from the remains?"
Options:
OPTION 1: Dragon Blood/Remains
If the party collected dragon scales, bones, or blood from Sahloknir (or any dragon):
Esbern: "Perfect. The seal can't tell the difference between blood in your veins and blood on your hands. Place the dragon remains on the seal."
Mechanic:
The party places dragon blood/scales/bones on the hand indentation
Esbern speaks an ancient Akaviri incantation
The seal glows red, recognizes the dragon essence, and opens
OPTION 2: Forced Entry (If No Dragon Blood)
If the party has no dragon remains:
Esbern: (frustrated) "Then we do this the hard way."
Options:
Magic: A powerful Destruction spell (Adept or higher) can shatter the ward (requires 15 FP and a Magic check)
Explosives: Dwarven oil + fire runes can blast the door (requires materials and an Agility check to set safely)
Brute Force: The party can attempt to physically break the ancient stone (multiple Might checks, takes time, alerts enemies)
OPTION 3: Esbern's Secret Knowledge
If all else fails, Esbern reveals he knows a bypass:
Esbern: "There's... another way. A Dovahzul phraseΓÇöDragon LanguageΓÇöthat forces the seal. I learned it from a text in the Arcanaeum. But using it will damage the door. It's sacrilege, defacing a Blades sanctuary. But if we have no choice..."
Mechanic:
Esbern speaks the Words of Power: "Zul Mey Gut" (Voice-Fool-Far)
The seal cracks, the door grinds open
Inside, some mechanisms are damaged (flavor only, doesn't affect the temple)

INSIDE SKY HAVEN TEMPLE
The Main Hall:
READ ALOUD:
"The door grinds open, revealing a vast hall carved from living stone. Pillars stretch toward a vaulted ceiling, and the air smells of dust and ancient incense. The walls are lined with empty weapon racks, broken training dummies, and faded banners bearing the symbol of the BladesΓÇöa dragon with a sword through its skull.
At the far end of the hall, dominating the entire wall, is Alduin's Wall.
It's enormousΓÇöthirty feet wide, twenty feet tall, covered in intricate carvings that seem to writhe in the torchlight. Dragons. Warriors. Battles. Prophecies. Thousands of years of history condensed into stone.
Esbern stands before it, tears in his eyes.
'By the gods,' he whispers. 'It's real. It's all here.'"

ALDUIN'S WALL
Esbern's Translation: He spends the next hour examining the wall, translating the Akaviri and Dovahzul inscriptions. The party can explore the temple, find loot, or rest.
What the Wall Shows (Esbern's Summary):
"This is the complete history of the Dragon War. Look hereΓÇö" (points to the top) "ΓÇöthis is Alduin at the height of his power. The World-Eater, worshipped by ancient Nords as a god. He and his dragons ruled through terror. Entire kingdoms burned. Humans were slaves."
(He moves his hand down)
"HereΓÇöthis is the rebellion. A man named Hakon One-Eye led the humans against the dragons. But they were losing. Dragon scales turned aside mortal weapons. Dragon breath incinerated armies. No matter how many humans fought, the dragons were unstoppable."
(He points to a specific section)
"Until this. Paarthurnax. Alduin's own lieutenant. He betrayed him. Taught humans the Thu'umΓÇöthe Voice. Gave them the power to fight back on equal terms."
(He traces a series of carvings)
"The humans created a Shout specifically to fight dragons. Dragonrend. It forces dragons to understand mortalityΓÇöto feel the fear of death. Dragons are immortal. They don't comprehend endings. Dragonrend makes them vulnerable. Grounds them. Allows mortals to kill them."
(He moves to the center of the wall)
"But even with Dragonrend, they couldn't kill Alduin. He was too strong. So they did something desperate. They used an Elder ScrollΓÇöa tear in time itselfΓÇöto cast Alduin forward through the centuries. They banished him, hoping future generations would be ready."
(He points to the bottom of the wall)
"And here. The prophecy. When Alduin returns, a Dragonborn will rise. A mortal with the soul of a dragon. They will learn Dragonrend. They will absorb dragon souls. They will stand at the Throat of the World and face Alduin in single combat."
(He turns to the party, and his voice is heavy)
"That's the prophecy. That's how it's supposed to happen. A hero. Chosen by fate. Blessed by the gods."
(Pause)
"But there is no Dragonborn. Which means... we follow the old path. We find Paarthurnax. We learn Dragonrend. We get the Elder Scroll. And we kill Alduin ourselves. Prophecy be damned."

THE PLAN
Esbern lays out the steps:
Step 1: Find Paarthurnax
"He's the key to everything. He taught humans the Thu'um onceΓÇöhe can do it again. The Greybeards worship him. He lives atop the Throat of the World, at the peak of High Hrothgar."
Step 2: Learn the Way of the Voice
"We're not Dragonborn. We can't naturally speak the Thu'um. But with training, mortals can learnΓÇöit just takes discipline. The Greybeards can teach us the basics. Paarthurnax can teach us Dragonrend."
Step 3: Obtain the Elder Scroll
"The same Elder Scroll the ancient Nords used is still out there. I have leads on its location. We'll need it to understand how they cast Alduin through timeΓÇöand possibly to weaken him when we fight."
Step 4: Kill Alduin
"Once we have Dragonrend, once we understand the Scroll, we find Alduin's lair and we end him. No prophecy. No chosen one. Just us."
Delphine's Addition (If Present):
"And after Alduin falls... Paarthurnax dies too."
Esbern: "DelphineΓÇö"
Delphine: "He's a dragon, Esbern. Alduin's brother. His lieutenant. Yes, he helped humans once. But he's still a dragon. And dragons always return to their nature. We can't risk it."
Esbern: (quietly) "Let's defeat Alduin first. Then we decide."

LOOT & REWARDS
Sky Haven Temple Contains:
Dragonbane: A unique Akaviri katana (One-Handed, Damage 10, Finesse, Special: +5 damage vs. dragons)
Blades Armor: Light armor sets (DR 3, Moon-Blessed: +1 FP, Special: +1 DR vs. dragons)
Blades Weapons: Various katanas and tantos (One-Handed, Damage 8, Finesse)
Ancient Texts: Skill books on combat, history, and dragon lore (+1 to relevant skills)
Gold: 500 gold in old Akaviri coins (historic value)
Esbern's Offer:
"Take what you need. These weapons were forged to kill dragons. You've earned them."

PHASE 5: THE THROAT OF THE WORLD
Timing: After Sky Haven Temple
 Duration: 1-2 sessions
HIGH HROTHGAR
The Journey: The party must climb the 7,000 steps to High Hrothgar, the monastery of the Greybeards.
The Greybeards: Four monks who have mastered the Way of the Voice. They speak in whispers because their full voice could shatter stone.
Master Arngeir: The only Greybeard who speaks normally. He greets the party:
Arngeir: "Travelers. We felt the Voice used in anger. We felt a dragon die. We expected... the Dragonborn. But you are not them."
Esbern's Response:
"Master Arngeir, I am Esbern, last of the Blades. These are the warriors who killed Sahloknir. There is no Dragonborn. Alduin returns, and we have no prophecy to save us. We need Paarthurnax. We need to learn Dragonrend. We need to stop the World-Eater ourselves."
Arngeir's Reaction: He is deeply troubled.
Arngeir: "Paarthurnax waits atop the mountain. But he waits for the Dragonborn, not... mercenaries. You seek Dragonrend? That Shout is a curse. It is hatred given form. It corrupts those who speak it. And you seek to learn it without the discipline of a lifetime's training?"
(He shakes his head)
Arngeir: "Paarthurnax will not see you. Not unless you prove yourselves worthy."

THE TRIALS
Arngeir's Test: The party must prove they can handle the Way of the Voice before being allowed to meet Paarthurnax.
Trial 1: Ro (Balance)
The party must meditate and achieve inner calm (Guile check)
Those who fail are overcome by emotion and cannot proceed
Trial 2: Dah (Push)
The Greybeards teach the party the Unrelenting Force Shout (Fus Ro Dah)
The party must demonstrate control by Shouting at targets without destroying them (Agility check for precision)
Trial 3: Strun (Storm)
The party must face a test of enduranceΓÇöstanding in a blizzard atop the monastery while the Greybeards Shout around them (Might check to resist being blown off the mountain)
Success: If the party passes all three trials:
Arngeir: (grudging respect) "You have... potential. More than I expected. Very well. The path to the summit is open. Paarthurnax will decide if you are worthy."

MEETING PAARTHURNAX
The Summit: The highest peak in Skyrim. Wind howls. Snow swirls. The air is thin.
The Dragon: Perched on the Word Wall is PaarthurnaxΓÇöan ancient dragon, his scales gray with age, his eyes wise and weary.
READ ALOUD:
"The dragon is enormous, but he does not move. He simply watches you approach with eyes that have seen millennia pass. When he speaks, his voice is deep, resonant, and... calm.
'Drem yol lok. Greetings. I have waited long for dov-ah-kiin. But you are not them. You are... dragonslayers. Dovah-lot. Dragon-hunters.'
(He tilts his head, studying you)
'Yet you killed Sahloknir. You stopped his resurrection. This was not foreseen. Perhaps... perhaps the prophecy is fluid. Perhaps there is another way.'"
Esbern's Introduction:
"Great Paarthurnax, I am Esbern of the Blades. We seek your help. Alduin returns. The dragons rise. But there is no Dragonborn to stop them. We must follow the old pathΓÇölearn Dragonrend, understand the Elder Scroll, and face Alduin ourselves."
Paarthurnax's Response:
"Dragonrend. Joor zah frul. The Shout that broke Alduin's power. It is a terrible weapon. It forces dragons to feel mortalityΓÇöto understand death. For creatures who are eternal, this is... agony. Madness. A violation of our very nature."
(He looks at each of them)
"Are you prepared to wield such a thing? To speak hatred and death into the world?"
The party must answer.
Paarthurnax (After Their Answer):
"Very well. I will teach you what I can. The Way of the Voice. The philosophy of restraint. And... if you prove worthy... I will help you obtain Dragonrend. But know this: that Shout is a curse. It corrupts those who use it. Even the ancient Nords who created it were changed by it."
"You must be strong. Not just in body, but in spirit. Or the Shout will consume you."

TRAINING MONTAGE
Over the next several days, Paarthurnax trains the party:
Day 1-3: Meditation and Breath
Learning to feel the Voice within themselves
Controlled breathing exercises
Resisting the urge to Shout in anger
Day 4-7: Basic Shouts
Mastering Fus (Force)
Learning Ro Dah (Balance Push)
Practicing on targets without killing
Day 8-10: Philosophy
Paarthurnax teaches the Way of the Voice
"The Thu'um is not a weapon. It is a tool. Used with restraint, it brings balance. Used with anger, it brings destruction."
The party learns discipline (mechanical benefit: +1 to Magic checks when using Shouts)
Day 11: The Offer
"You have learned well. Better than I expected. You are ready for the next step. To learn Dragonrend, you must witness its creation. You must see the moment it was forgedΓÇöthe moment three ancient heroes spoke their hatred into existence."
"This requires the Elder Scroll. The same Scroll that cast Alduin through time. With it, you can look back and see that moment. Learn the Shout. And understand the price."

ESBERN'S SUSPICION
Throughout the training, Esbern watches Paarthurnax carefully.
Esbern (Quietly to the Party, When Paarthurnax Is Not Near):
"Don't trust him. He's a dragon. Yes, he helped us once. But dragons are eternal. They don't change. They can't change. He served Alduin for centuriesΓÇöruled alongside him, burned cities, enslaved humans. Then he betrayed him. What's to stop him from betraying us?"
Delphine (If Present):
"Esbern's right. I've seen what dragons do. Even the 'good' ones. They're predators. Conquerors. It's in their nature. When Alduin is dead, Paarthurnax will be the oldest, the strongest. He could take Alduin's place. Rule the dragons. And we'd have traded one tyrant for another."
The Tension: This plants the seed for the later choice. Let the party debate among themselves.

PHASE 6: THE ELDER SCROLL
Timing: After training with Paarthurnax
 Duration: 1 session
THE SEARCH
Paarthurnax's Guidance:
"The Elder Scroll you seek was lost after the Dragon War. But it was not destroyed. Elder Scrolls cannot be destroyed. They exist outside time. They are time."
"Seek the scholars who study such things. The College of Winterhold. Or the Moth Priests of Cyrodiil. They may know where it rests."
Esbern's Knowledge:
"I've researched this. There's a Moth Priest in SkyrimΓÇöbrought north by the Empire to study a Scroll in their possession. If we can find him, we can find the Scroll."
The Trail:
The party investigates and learns the Moth Priest (Dexion Evicus) was traveling to Forebears' Holdout
They find him there, but he's been attacked by vampires (foreshadowing Dawnguard content if you're running that)
He's blind (Moth Priests go blind from reading Scrolls) but alive
He tells them the Elder Scroll is in Blackreach, hidden in the Tower of Mzark
BLACKREACH
The Journey: The party must navigate the ruins of Alftand, a Dwarven ruin, to reach the underground city of Blackreach.
Blackreach: A massive, bioluminescent cavern filled with Falmer, Chaurus, and Dwarven automatons.
Tower of Mzark: A Dwarven mechanism designed to store the Elder Scroll. The party must solve a puzzle (Lexicon Receptacle) to access it.
The Elder Scroll: When retrieved, it hums with temporal energy. Reading it requires preparation (Paarthurnax will guide them later).

PHASE 7: THE TIME-WOUND
Timing: After obtaining the Elder Scroll
 Duration: Part of a session
RETURN TO THE THROAT OF THE WORLD
Paarthurnax:
"You have the Scroll. Now you must read it. But not here. There is a place where time is... thin. Where the past bleeds into the present. The Time-Wound, created when the ancient Nords cast Alduin forward. It exists atop this mountain, near where we stand."
The Time-Wound: A shimmering distortion in the air, barely visible.
The Reading: One party member (chosen by the group) reads the Elder Scroll while standing in the Time-Wound.
The Vision:
READ ALOUD:
"The world dissolves. You are standing on this same mountaintop, but it is thousands of years ago. The sky is dark with dragons. Below, you see armies clashingΓÇöNords fighting for their freedom.
Before you stand three warriors: Hakon One-Eye, a Nord hero with a massive battleaxe. Gormlaith Golden-Hilt, a warrior-woman with fury in her eyes. Felldir the Old, a mage with an Elder Scroll in his hands.
And descending from the sky, roaring with rage, is Alduin.
The three heroes stand together. They speak in unison, their voices layered with power:
'JOOR ZAH FRUL!'
The Shout hits Alduin like a physical blow. For the first time, the immortal dragon feels. He feels the weight of mortality. The terror of endings. The finite nature of existence.
He crashes to the ground, stunned and vulnerable.
The heroes rush forward to strike, but Alduin is too strong. Even weakened, even mortal for this brief moment, he fights back.
Felldir raises the Elder Scroll. He speaks words in a language you don't understandΓÇöthe language of time itself.
A rift opens. Alduin roars in defiance as he's pulled into it, forward through the centuries, banished but not destroyed.
The last thing you see is Hakon's face, filled with grim determination:
'This isn't over. Someday, someone will have to finish what we started.'
The vision ends. You're back on the mountaintop, gasping for air. But the Words are in your mind now. Burned into your soul.
Joor. Zah. Frul.
Mortal. Finite. Temporary.
You have learned Dragonrend."

THE AFTERMATH
Paarthurnax:
"You have seen it. The moment Dragonrend was born. The moment three mortals spoke their hatred of dragons into existence. Do you understand what you have learned? That Shout is not just a weapon. It is a philosophy. It is the belief that dragons are wrong. That immortality is a sin. That we must end."
(He looks sad)
"Every time you speak those Words, you speak that hatred. You tell the world that dragons must die. Even me."
Esbern:
"Good. Because that's exactly what needs to happen."

PHASE 8: THE IMPOSSIBLE CHOICE
Timing: After learning Dragonrend, BEFORE facing Alduin
 Duration: Climactic roleplay scene
THE CONFRONTATION
The Setup: The party returns to Sky Haven Temple (or another neutral location) to prepare for the final assault on Alduin.
Esbern's Speech: He gathers the party together.
Esbern: "We have everything we need. Dragonrend. The Elder Scroll. The knowledge. Tomorrow, we find Alduin's lair. We use Dragonrend to ground him. We fight him as mortals fought him three thousand years ago. And this time, we finish it."
(He pauses)
Esbern: "But there's one more thing that must be done. Before we face Alduin, Paarthurnax must die."
Delphine (If Present):
"He's right. Paarthurnax is Alduin's brother. His lieutenant. Yes, he betrayed Alduin onceΓÇöbut what happens when Alduin is dead? Paarthurnax is the oldest, the strongest. He could take Alduin's place. Rule the dragons. And we'd have traded one tyrant for another."
Esbern:
"The Blades exist to protect mortals from dragons. All dragons. Even the ones who smile and speak philosophy. Especially those ones. They're the most dangerous because they make us forget what they are."
"Paarthurnax ruled alongside Alduin for centuries. He burned cities. He enslaved humans. He was a tyrant. Yes, he changed sides. But he's still a dragon. And dragons... dragons always return to their nature. It's inevitable."
"Kill him now. Before we face Alduin. It's the only way to be sure."

THE PARTY'S RESPONSE
Let the party debate. This is a critical decision point. Give them time.
Arguments in Favor of Killing Paarthurnax:
He's a dragonΓÇöpredators by nature
He did serve Alduin for centuries
He could take over after Alduin's death
Esbern and Delphine are experienced dragon-hunters
Better safe than sorry
Arguments Against Killing Paarthurnax:
He's been helping them
He's spent 3,000 years teaching restraint
He's the only one who can guide dragons toward peace
Killing him would betray trust
The Greybeards would never forgive them

CONFRONTING PAARTHURNAX
If the party decides to kill him:
They return to the Throat of the World. Paarthurnax is waiting.
Paarthurnax: "Drem yol lok. You return. Are you ready to face Alduin?"
If they reveal their intent:
(He is silent for a long moment)
"I see. The Blades have spoken. And you have listened."
(He does not move to defend himself)
"I understand. I am dov. My nature is domination. I have fought this nature for three thousand years, but it never leaves me. If you believe I am too dangerous to live, then strike. I will not resist."
"But know this: I am the last who remembers the Way of the Voice. The last who can teach restraint. When I die, that knowledge dies with me. The remaining dragons will have no guide. No teacher. They will return to their natureΓÇöconquest and destruction. You will have chosen security over hope."
(He bows his head)
"The choice is yours. But choose wisely."
The party must decide.

PATH A: KILL PAARTHURNAX
The Fight: Paarthurnax does not resist. He could fightΓÇöhe's an ancient dragon, more powerful than SahloknirΓÇöbut he chooses not to.
Mechanics:
He has 100 HP, DR 8, and devastating breath attacks
But he does not use them
He simply... accepts death
Each attack the party makes, he speaks:
Paarthurnax (As They Attack):
"Krosis. Forgive me. I tried to change. I tried to be better."
(Another blow)
"Perhaps... perhaps they are right. Perhaps dragons cannot change."
(Another blow)
"Zu'u lost dii korah. I have done my duty. The Voice will endure... or it will not."
(Final blow)
"Drem... yol... lok..."
He dies. His body burns away, leaving only bones and a word wall behind.

Immediate Consequences:
Esbern:
(Standing over the remains, solemn) "It's done. You've done the right thing. The hard thing. The thing that needed to be done."
(He places a hand on their shoulder)
"The Blades will remember this. You honored our oathΓÇöprotect the people, at any cost."
Delphine (If Present):
(She's conflictedΓÇörelief mixed with grief) "He... he didn't even fight. I expected... I don't know what I expected. But not that."
(She shakes her head)
"It was still the right choice. We can't take chances. Not with dragons."
The Greybeards: When the party descends the mountain, Master Arngeir is waiting at High Hrothgar. His face is stone.
Arngeir: "You have murdered the master. The last who remembered the Dragon War. The last who could teach the Way of the Voice."
(His voice is cold, final)
Arngeir: "You are not welcome here. Not now. Not ever. Leave. And do not return."
The Greybeards turn their backs. The door to High Hrothgar closes. Forever.

Impact on Alduin Fight:
No Paarthurnax to provide guidance or support
The party must face Alduin alone with only Esbern and Delphine
Slightly harder fight (no dragon ally)
Epilogue Consequences:
Dragons scatter without leadership after Alduin's death
Some are hunted down by mortals and the Blades
Others terrorize the countryside, leaderless and angry
It becomes a war of attritionΓÇödragons vs. mortals, ongoing
The Blades reform as dragon-hunters, constantly pursuing threats
Skyrim is "safe" but scarred, always watching the skies
The Way of the Voice is lostΓÇöno more training available
The Greybeards refuse all contact with the party
Esbern and Delphine are satisfied but haunted by Paarthurnax's final words

PATH B: SPARE PAARTHURNAX
The Confrontation with Esbern:
Party: "We're not killing Paarthurnax."
Esbern: (long silence, then:)
"What?"
Party explains their reasoning.
Esbern: (rising anger)
"You're refusing? After everything? After what he is? He's a dragon! He served Alduin for centuries! He could betray us tomorrow, next week, next year! And you're willing to take that risk?!"
Delphine (If Present):
"Esbern, maybeΓÇö"
Esbern: (cutting her off)
"No. NO. The Blades have one purposeΓÇöprotect mortals from dragons. If you won't do that, then you're not Blades. You're dragon-lovers. Fools who'll get everyone killed."
(He grabs his gear)
"I spent forty years in hiding. Forty years waiting for the Dragonborn. For someone who could end this. And when they don't come, when I'm forced to turn to you, you betray everything the Blades stand for."
(He heads for the door)
"The Blades die here. I am the last, and I will not serve those who protect dragons. Face Alduin if you want. Win or lose, I don't care anymore. I'm done."
Delphine (If Present): She's torn. She looks at the party, then at Esbern.
Delphine: "Esbern... they killed a dragon. They're trying to save Skyrim. Isn't that enough?"
Esbern: "Not if they let Paarthurnax live."
Delphine: (after a long pause, quietly) "Then I'm sorry. But my oath is to the Blades. To Esbern. Not to you."
(She follows Esbern out.)
They leave. The party is alone.

Immediate Consequences:
Esbern and Delphine are gone
The Blades are finished
The party loses access to Blades equipment and knowledge
But they keep Paarthurnax
The Greybeards: When the party returns to High Hrothgar:
Arngeir: "You spared the master. You chose wisdom over fear. You have our gratitude."
(He bows)
Arngeir: "The Way of the Voice endures because of you. We will continue to teach. To guide. To offer what knowledge we can."
Paarthurnax:
"You chose hope over certainty. You trusted a dragon. This is... rare. Perhaps mortals and dov can coexist. Perhaps the cycle of violence can be broken."
"I will guide my kin as best I can. Some will listen. Some will not. But I will try."

Impact on Alduin Fight:
Paarthurnax provides guidance and moral support
He may join the fight at a critical moment (dragon ally)
Slightly easier fight
Epilogue Consequences:
Paarthurnax becomes the leader of dragons after Alduin's death
He teaches the Way of the Voice to dragons who will listen
Some dragons follow, embracing peace and restraint
Some dragons refuse, continue to terrorize Skyrim
It's a gambleΓÇöbetter than full-scale war, but not perfect safety
Skyrim has dragon allies AND dragon enemies
The Blades are gone forever
Esbern dies bitter and alone, believing the party doomed the world
Delphine (if alive) disappears, possibly joining Esbern in exile

PATH C: CONVINCE ESBERN (Very Hard)
The Challenge: The party attempts to convince Esbern that Paarthurnax should live and that the Blades must evolve.
Mechanics: This requires three separate Very Hard (-6) Guile (Persuasion) checks, each representing a different line of argument.
Argument 1: Evidence of Change "Paarthurnax has proven himself over 3,000 years. He's had countless opportunities to return to tyranny. He hasn't."
Guile Check (Very Hard, -6):
Success: Esbern pauses. "Three thousand years... that is a long time. Longer than any Blade has lived. Longer than the Empire has existed. If he were going to betray us, he's had ample opportunity."
Failure: "Time means nothing to dragons. They're immortal. Three thousand years is a heartbeat to them. He could be patient. Waiting."

Argument 2: Practical Necessity "We need him. Not just for Alduin, but for after. Who else can lead the dragons toward peace? Who else can mediate between mortals and dov?"
Guile Check (Very Hard, -6):
Success: Esbern's resolve wavers. "You're saying... we need a dragon to control dragons. A warden, not just hunters."
Failure: "That's appeasement. Letting the enemy police themselves. It never works."

Argument 3: Legacy and Evolution "The Blades were founded to protect people. Not to hunt every dragon forever. If we kill Paarthurnax, we're not protectorsΓÇöwe're just killers. The world has changed. The Blades must change with it."
Guile Check (Very Hard, -6):
Success: Esbern sits down heavily. This is the hardest one for him to hear.
Failure: "The Blades' purpose is clear. If we abandon it, we abandon everything."

If All Three Checks Succeed:
Esbern: (after a very long silence)
"Perhaps... perhaps you're right. Perhaps I've been so focused on what the Blades were that I couldn't see what they could become."
(He looks at his hands)
"We were dragon-slayers. For millennia, that's all we were. Hunt. Kill. Protect. But in a world where dragons return... where they can't all be killed... perhaps we must be something else."
"Dragon-wardens. Watching. Mediating. Preventing wars before they start. Hunting the ones who can't be redeemed, yes. But... working with the ones who can."
(He looks at Paarthurnax, when they next meet him)
"I will spare you, dragon. But I will watch you. Always. If you falterΓÇöif you return to your natureΓÇöI will know. And I will act."
Paarthurnax: "That is... acceptable. Zu'u los ni oblaanΓÇöI am not eternal in my goodness. But while I live, I will guide my kin toward the Voice, not the fire. And if I fail... you will do what must be done."

Delphine (If Present): She's shocked.
Delphine: "Esbern... are you sure?"
Esbern: "No. I'm not. But they're rightΓÇöthe world has changed. If we cling to the past, we die with it. The Blades must evolve, or the Blades must end."
(He looks at the party)
Esbern: "You've given me something I lostΓÇöhope. Not certainty. Not safety. But hope. That's enough."

Immediate Consequences:
Esbern agrees to a "New Blades" philosophy
Watchers and mediators, not just hunters
They hunt rogue dragons and protect peaceful ones
Greybeards are grateful
Paarthurnax lives
Thu'um training continues
Impact on Alduin Fight:
Paarthurnax provides maximum support
Esbern provides tactical knowledge
Both philosophies (combat and restraint) combine
Easiest version of the fight
The party has allies on all sides
Epilogue Consequences:
Best possible outcome
Paarthurnax leads willing dragons to peace
The "New Blades" hunt rogue dragons and protect peaceful ones
Skyrim has dragon allies working alongside reformed Blades
Not perfect peace, but genuine coexistence
Some dragons still cause trouble, but they're the minority
Esbern finds new purpose, dies with hope instead of bitterness
Delphine (if alive) becomes a mediator between dragons and mortals
The Way of the Voice endures and spreads

If Any Check Fails: Esbern is not convinced. The party must choose between Path A (kill Paarthurnax) or Path B (spare him and lose the Blades).

PHASE 9: FACE ALDUIN
Timing: After the choice regarding Paarthurnax
 Duration: Final boss fight session
FINDING ALDUIN'S LAIR
Paarthurnax's Knowledge (If Alive):
"Alduin will return to SovngardeΓÇöthe Nordic afterlife. It is there he devours the souls of the dead, growing stronger. You must follow him. Confront him in the realm of the gods."
Esbern's Knowledge (If Still With Party):
"There's a portal to Sovngarde at SkuldafnΓÇöa dragon temple in the Jerall Mountains. It's heavily guarded by dragons and draugr. Getting there will be a battle. But if Paarthurnax is right, that's where Alduin is."
Delphine's Addition (If Present):
"We'll need a way to get to Skuldafn. It's on a mountain peakΓÇöinaccessible by foot. We'll need to... convince a dragon to take us."
Paarthurnax (If Alive):
"Odahviing. One of Alduin's generals. He is proud. Arrogant. If you challenge himΓÇölure him to a place where he can be trappedΓÇöyou may be able to force him to serve you."

TRAPPING ODAHVIING (Optional)
The Setup: The party uses the Dragonrend Shout to force Odahviing to land in Whiterun (the Jarl agrees to help trap him in Dragonsreach).
The Fight: Odahviing is a powerful dragon (TL 3 Boss). The party uses Dragonrend to ground him, then battles until he's weakened.
The Capture: Once reduced to low HP, Odahviing is trapped in Dragonsreach's great hall.
The Negotiation: Odahviing: "You are strong. Stronger than I expected. Very well. I will take you to Skuldafn. But know thisΓÇöAlduin grows stronger by the day. You may already be too late."

SKULDAFN
The Assault: A massive dragon temple crawling with draugr and dragons.
Key Encounters:
Dragon priests
Draugr deathlords
Frost dragons
The Portal: At the summit of Skuldafn is a portal to Sovngarde, activated by a staff found in the temple.

SOVNGARDE
The Afterlife: A realm of eternal mist, where Nordic heroes feast in the Hall of Valor.
The Obstacle: Alduin has filled Sovngarde with mist, trapping souls and preventing them from reaching the Hall.
The Heroes: The party meets the three ancient Nord heroes from the vision: Hakon, Gormlaith, and Felldir. They agree to help.

THE FINAL BATTLE
The Arena: A cleared space before the Hall of Valor. The mist parts. Alduin descends.
The Fight:
Phase 1: Alduin is flying. The party uses Dragonrend to ground him.
Phase 2: Alduin lands. The party + the three heroes attack. Paarthurnax (if alive) joins.
Phase 3: When reduced to half HP, Alduin takes to the sky again. Repeat Dragonrend.
Phase 4: Final phase. Alduin fights with desperation.
Mechanics:
Alduin (Boss):
HP: 300 (divided across phases)
DR: 10
Attacks: Meteor Storm (AoE), Fire Breath, Tail Swipe, Bite
Special: Can only be damaged while grounded (requires Dragonrend)
Allies:
Hakon, Gormlaith, Felldir (each deals 15 damage/turn)
Paarthurnax (if alive, deals 20 damage/turn)
Esbern and Delphine (if present, provide tactical bonuses)
Victory: When Alduin reaches 0 HP:
READ ALOUD:
"Alduin staggers, his wings torn, his scales shattered. For the first time in his existence, he feels fear.
He tries to speakΓÇöto bargain, to threatenΓÇöbut the words die in his throat.
The final blow lands. Alduin, the World-Eater, the First-Born of Akatosh, the dragon who devoured the last world... dies.
His body does not burn away. Instead, it dissolves into lightΓÇöstreams of soul-energy that spiral upward into the sky, dissipating into nothing.
The mist clears. The souls trapped in Sovngarde are free. In the distance, you hear the sound of celebration from the Hall of Valor.
It's over. Alduin is dead. The world is saved.
You did it."

