END OF BLADES QUESTLINE DOCUMENTATION

APPENDIX: THE BLADES QUESTLINE
CAMPAIGN CLOCK: THE LAST BLADE
This questline represents the complete arc of Esbern and the Blades in a world without a Dragonborn. It begins with betrayal and ends with an impossible choice that will shape Skyrim's future.

PHASE 0: THE BETRAYAL (Adventure Conclusion)
What Happens: If the party betrays Delphine by informing the Thalmor about the Sleeping Giant Inn, this questline activates.
Immediate Consequences:
Within 2-3 days, a Thalmor strike team raids the Sleeping Giant Inn
Delphine fights but is overwhelmed (she's outnumbered 8-to-1)
She's taken alive to the Thalmor Embassy
Orgnar (the innkeeper) survives but is terrified and traumatized
Riverwood becomes much more hostile to strangers
Delphine's Status:
Captured, Not Killed: The Thalmor know she's a Blade - this is a MASSIVE intelligence coup
She's being interrogated for information about remaining Blades, hideouts, and operations
She hasn't broken yet, but she's suffering
She's held in the Embassy dungeon, guarded heavily
Esbern's Discovery:
Esbern and Delphine have a dead drop system (coded messages left in hidden locations)
When Delphine misses her scheduled check-in (3 days later), Esbern knows something is wrong
He investigates carefully through his network of beggars and informants
Within a week, he learns: "Thalmor raided Riverwood. Woman matching Delphine's description captured."
Esbern goes into deeper hiding, grief-stricken but grimly determined

PHASE 1: THE SUMMONS
Trigger: Party kills Sahloknir at Kynesgrove
Timeline: 3-5 days after the dragon's death
THE NEWS SPREADS
Dragon attacks are unprecedented. The news spreads like wildfire through Skyrim's taverns, trading posts, and courier networks.
What People Are Saying:
"A dragon attacked Kynesgrove! Burned half the village!"
"Group of mercenaries killed it - some kind of royal agents"
"They call themselves 'Wardens' - chartered by the High King himself"
"One of them punched the dragon so hard it exploded" (exaggerated, but based on Kyboh's hit)
Esbern's Intelligence Network: Esbern maintains contacts throughout Skyrim:
Beggars who eavesdrop and trade information for coin
Stable workers who hear travelers' stories
Couriers who pass through Riften regularly
Thieves Guild contacts (through mutual necessity, not alliance)
Within days, multiple sources bring him the same story: "The Wardens killed a dragon at Kynesgrove."
ESBERN'S DECISION
Esbern is alone. Delphine is gone (captured or dead, he doesn't know which). The dragon apocalypse is beginning, and there is NO Dragonborn.
He makes a desperate calculation:
"They killed a dragon. Most warriors couldn't even scratch one. They're alive, which means they're skilled. They're all I have. I must reach out."
THE CONTACT
Esbern doesn't approach directly - he's too paranoid. He uses an intermediary.
The Messenger: A street urchin in Riften (or wherever the party is staying) approaches them with a sealed letter. The boy says: "A old man paid me five septims to give you this. Said you'd know what it means."
The Letter:
To the Wardens of Kynesgrove,
You killed the dragon Sahloknir. I know what's coming. I know why the dragons return. I can help you kill more.
I have knowledge - dragon lairs, their weaknesses, ancient techniques. I have weapons and armor from the Dragon War itself. And I know how to stop this permanently.
Meet me in Riften. The Ratway, Warrens district. Ask for "the scholar." Come alone or together, but come soon.
The World-Eater rises, and we have no Dragonborn to save us.
- A Friend
GM Notes:
The letter is written in a shaky but educated hand
The wax seal is broken/unmarked (Esbern doesn't advertise the Blades)
The phrase "World-Eater" should intrigue anyone familiar with Nord mythology
The mention of "no Dragonborn" is ominous and true

PHASE 2: THE RATWAY MEETING
Location: The Ratway Warrens, Riften
 Tone: Paranoid, desperate, but hopeful
THE DESCENT
The Ratway is Riften's underbelly - a maze of tunnels beneath the city where the desperate and criminal hide. To reach the Warrens, the party must navigate:
The Ragged Flagon:
A thieves' den and tavern run by the Thieves Guild
NPCs here are suspicious but not hostile (unless the party has pissed off the Guild)
Asking for "the scholar" gets knowing looks: "Oh, the crazy old man. Yeah, he's back in the Warrens. Good luck."
The Warrens:
The deepest, dampest section
Esbern's "room" is a converted storage chamber with a reinforced door
The door has multiple locks and a viewing slot
THE GREETING
When the party knocks, a suspicious voice comes through the slot:
Esbern: "Who sent you? Who gave you this location?"
Correct Answers:
"You did. Through a letter."
"A street urchin. You paid him five septims."
"We killed a dragon. You said you could help."
Wrong Answers / Hostile Approach:
Esbern assumes they're Thalmor agents
He refuses to open the door
Party must make Very Hard (-6) Guile (Persuasion) check to convince him
THE TEST
Even if they give correct answers, Esbern tests them through the door:
Esbern: "The dragon at Kynesgrove. How did you kill it?"
He's listening for specific details that prove they were actually there:
Description of Sahloknir's appearance (bronze/green scales, frost breath)
Mention of Alduin's presence (the black dragon that resurrected it)
The dragon's soul being absorbed (by someone? Into the sky? Unclear?)
If They Pass: The locks click open. The door swings inward.
ESBERN'S APPEARANCE
READ ALOUD:
"The man who opens the door looks ancient. He's at least seventy, with a long grey beard and wild hair that hasn't seen a comb in weeks. His robes are travel-stained and patched, and his hands shake slightly as he ushers you inside.
But his eyes - his eyes are sharp, intelligent, and burning with desperate intensity.
The room behind him is cramped and cluttered. Every surface is covered with books, scrolls, maps, and notes. A bed in the corner looks unused. The walls are plastered with drawings - dragon anatomy, ancient runes, star charts, timelines.
This is not a hiding place. This is a research bunker.
He locks the door behind you with shaking hands, then turns.
'Thank the Divines. You came. You actually came.'"
THE PITCH
Esbern doesn't waste time with pleasantries. He's been alone too long, and the apocalypse is here.
Esbern's Introduction:
"I am Esbern. Last of the Blades. You don't know that name anymore - we were wiped out thirty years ago by the Thalmor. Hunted. Murdered. Our order destroyed because we served the Dragonborn Emperors, and the Aldmeri Dominion wanted us gone."
(He gestures to the walls covered in notes)
"I've spent three decades hiding in sewers and attics, researching, searching for the one thing that could save us: the Dragonborn. The prophecy is clear - when the dragons return, the Dragonborn will rise to stop them."
(His voice breaks slightly)
"But I've searched everywhere. Every rumor, every legend, every potential sign. And I've found nothing. No Dragonborn walks Skyrim. Which means we face the end of the world with no hero to save us."
(He looks directly at the party)
"You killed Sahloknir. You did what most armies couldn't do. You survived a dragon attack and struck back. That makes you the only hope I have left."
What Esbern Offers:
Knowledge:


Dragon lairs and migration patterns
Elemental weaknesses (frost dragons vs fire, etc.)
Anatomical vulnerabilities (wing joints, throat, eyes)
Thu'um (Shout) warnings and counters
Equipment:


Location of Sky Haven Temple (ancient Blades sanctuary)
Dragonbane (legendary Blades sword, dragon-slaying enchantment)
Blades Armor (light armor, designed for dragon combat)
Ancient potions and gear
A Plan:


"I know how the ancient Nords defeated Alduin the first time"
"I know where to find the answers we need"
"I know who can teach us to fight dragons as equals"
What Esbern Needs:
"Help me rebuild the Blades. Not the old order - that's dead. A new one. Dragon-killers. Protectors of Skyrim. Help me stop Alduin before he devours the world."
(He pauses)
"Please. You're all I have left."
THE DELPHINE QUESTION
If the party asks about other Blades, or if Esbern trusts them enough, he reveals:
Esbern: (voice tight with pain) "There was one other. Delphine. My... my friend. We worked together for years. She was in Riverwood, running an inn as cover, gathering intelligence."
(He looks away)
"She went silent three weeks ago. Missed our scheduled contact. I sent inquiries through my network. The Thalmor raided her inn. She's... she's either dead or captured."
(If the party looks guilty, he notices)
Esbern: "Why? Do you know something about this?"
GM Note: This is where the party's betrayal can come to light. How they handle this will determine Esbern's trust level:
Lie Successfully (Very Hard -6 Guile check): Esbern believes them, continues as planned
Tell the Truth: Esbern is devastated but pragmatic - "You... you did this. You gave her to them. Why? No - it doesn't matter. She's gone. And you're still all I have. Damn you."
Lie and Fail: Esbern sees through it, becomes permanently suspicious of the party
THE FIRST QUEST: PROOF OF COMMITMENT
Before revealing everything, Esbern wants proof the party is serious.
Esbern: "I need to know you're committed. There's a dragon lair - Bonestrewn Crest, in the mountains east of Windhelm. Ancient texts say a dragon named Nahagliiv has returned there. Kill it. Bring me proof. Then I'll take you to Sky Haven Temple and show you everything."
The Mission:
Travel to Bonestrewn Crest
Fight and kill Nahagliiv (use standard dragon stat block for party's tier)
Return with proof (dragon scales, bones, or just their word if Esbern trusts them)
Reward:
Esbern's full trust
Invitation to Sky Haven Temple
Advancement to Phase 3

PHASE 3: SKY HAVEN TEMPLE
Trigger: Party kills Nahagliiv and returns to Esbern
Location: Karthspire, The Reach
THE JOURNEY
Esbern leads the party to the Reach, to a remote canyon called Karthspire.
Travel Dialogue:
During the journey, Esbern opens up:
On the Blades: "We were founded in the First Era to serve the Dragonborn Emperors. Reman, Tiber Septim, the Septim Dynasty - we were their eyes, their swords, their shields. When the Septims fell and the Thalmor rose, we became targets. The Great War ended with the White-Gold Concordat, and one of its terms was our destruction. The Empire we served for thousands of years... they let us die."
On Delphine: "She and I escaped the purge. We've been running ever since. She was always braver than me - she stayed active, gathering intelligence, making contacts. I just... hid and researched. Maybe if I'd been braver, I could have protected her."
On Dragons: "Alduin is the World-Eater. The firstborn of Akatosh. In the Merethic Era, he ruled over mortals with tyranny and cruelty. The ancient Nords rebelled, and with the help of Paarthurnax - Alduin's own lieutenant who betrayed him - they learned the Thu'um. They couldn't kill Alduin, so they used an Elder Scroll to cast him forward through time. And now... time has caught up."
KARTHSPIRE
The canyon is ancient and overgrown. A river runs through it, and carved into the cliff face is a massive stone door - the entrance to Sky Haven Temple.
The Approach:
The area is infested with Forsworn (they've claimed the canyon as territory)
Party must fight through or sneak past them
Esbern can provide tactical advice but won't fight (he's too old/scared)
THE BLOOD SEAL
At the entrance, there's a puzzle: three pillars with rotating animal symbols (snake, whale, eagle - solution found in the environment).
But the real obstacle is the final door:
READ ALOUD:
"Beyond the pillars, the passage opens into a carved chamber. At the far end stands a massive circular door of stone, easily twelve feet tall. In its center is a mechanism - a shallow bowl carved into the rock, and above it, ancient Akaviri script.
Esbern approaches, reading the inscription aloud:
'Blood of the Dragonborn. Blood of the Dragon. The oath sealed in fire and scale.'
He turns to you, his expression grim.
'This seal was designed to respond to Dragonborn blood - the essence of Akatosh carried in mortal veins. But there is no Dragonborn.'"
THE SOLUTION
Esbern has spent years researching this exact problem.
Esbern: "The seal is designed to recognize dragon blood in mortal form. But what if we give it... actual dragon blood?"
(He pulls out a vial from his pack)
"I've carried this for thirty years. Blood from the last dragon killed before they vanished. It's degraded, barely potent. But combined with fresh dragon blood - from Sahloknir, from Nahagliiv - it might be enough."
The Ritual:
If the party collected dragon blood/scales/bones, Esbern can perform a ritual:
Mix the old blood with the new
Speak the Akaviri oath in Dovahzul
Pour the mixture into the bowl
The door responds.
READ ALOUD:
"The blood seeps into the stone. For a moment, nothing happens.
Then, a sound - a deep, rumbling grinding of stone on stone. Ancient mechanisms, dormant for thousands of years, creak to life. The circular door begins to roll aside, revealing a passage beyond lit by natural light filtering from above.
Esbern stands there, tears in his eyes.
'After all these years... we're home.'"
INSIDE SKY HAVEN TEMPLE
READ ALOUD:
"The temple is a marvel. Built into the mountain itself, it's a combination of fortress and sanctuary. The main hall is dominated by an enormous stone relief carved into the far wall - easily forty feet wide and twenty feet tall.
It depicts dragons and mortals in battle, ancient warriors wielding swords and bows, and at the center, a figure wreathed in light confronting a massive black dragon.
The room is dusty but intact. Weapon racks line the walls. Bookshelves hold ancient texts. Training dummies stand ready. Everything is preserved, waiting.
Esbern walks to the center of the room and spreads his arms.
'Alduin's Wall. The prophecy of the Dragonborn.'"
ALDUIN'S WALL
Esbern approaches the wall and begins reading the carved images like a story:
Esbern's Narration:
"This wall was carved during the Dragon War, thousands of years ago. It tells the complete prophecy of Alduin's return and defeat."
(He points to sections as he explains)
Panel 1 - The Dragon War: "Here - Alduin ruled over mortals with cruelty. The ancient Nords rebelled. This figure here - that's Paarthurnax, Alduin's lieutenant, teaching the first Tongues the Thu'um."
Panel 2 - The Banishment: "They couldn't kill Alduin. He was too powerful. So they used this - the Elder Scroll. They created a Shout called Dragonrend that forced Alduin to land, to understand mortality. Then they cast him forward through time."
Panel 3 - The Prophecy: "And here - the prophecy. 'When misrule takes its place at the eight corners of the world, when the Brass Tower walks and Time is reshaped, when the thrice-blessed fail and the Red Tower trembles, when the Dragonborn Ruler loses his throne, and the White Tower falls... then shall the sons of Skyrim spill their own blood.'"
(He looks at the party)
"Every condition has been met. The Oblivion Crisis. The fall of the Septim Dynasty. The Great War. And hereΓÇö" (points to the final panel) "ΓÇöthe Dragonborn confronts Alduin and defeats him."
(Long pause)
"But there is no Dragonborn."
THE DESPERATE PLAN
Esbern: "I've studied this wall through transcriptions and fragments for thirty years. The prophecy is clear about the Dragonborn's role. But it also shows something else - how the ancient Nords defeated Alduin the FIRST time."
(He points to specific details)
"Three things were needed:
1. Dragonrend - The Shout that forces dragons to land, to comprehend death. Without it, Alduin cannot be truly harmed.
2. The Elder Scroll - The same scroll used to banish him originally. It may be needed again.
3. Paarthurnax - Alduin's brother, who betrayed him and taught mortals the Voice. He's still alive. He's been living on the Throat of the World, waiting for the Dragonborn."
(He turns to face them directly)
"We don't have a Dragonborn. So we follow the old path. We find Paarthurnax. We learn what he knows. We get Dragonrend. We obtain the Elder Scroll. And we kill Alduin ourselves."
The Party's Choice:
This is the moment the party can:
Commit to the plan: "We're in. Let's kill a god."
Question it: "Is this even possible without a Dragonborn?"
Refuse: "This is insane. Find someone else."
Esbern's Response to Doubt:
"Is it possible? I don't know. Probably not. The prophecy is clear - the Dragonborn defeats Alduin. But what choice do we have? Wait for a hero who isn't coming? Watch the world burn?"
(He looks at his hands)
"I'm an old man. I've spent my entire life running and hiding. Delphine is gone. The Blades are dead. This is my last chance to matter. To finish what my order started."
(He looks up at them)
"And you've killed two dragons. TWO. That's more than anyone has done in four thousand years. If anyone can do this... it's you."
THE ARMORY
If the party commits, Esbern gives them access to the temple's equipment:
Dragonbane:
A katana with a glowing Akaviri inscription on the blade
Stats: Damage 14 (One-Handed Sword, Finesse)
Enchantment: +10 Damage vs Dragons (total of 24 damage)
Property: On Critical Success vs dragons, the blade burns with dragonfire, dealing an additional +5 Fire Damage
Blades Armor (Light Armor Set):
Stats: DR 3 (Light Armor)
Property: Dragon Resistance - Take half damage from dragon breath weapons
Appearance: Red and black leather with Akaviri styling, scaled patterns
Blades Sword (Standard):
Stats: Damage 8 (One-Handed Sword, Finesse)
For NPCs/Companions: Esbern can arm followers with these
Ancient Potions:
3x Potion of Dragon Resistance (Take half damage from all dragon attacks for 3 rounds)
2x Potion of Fortified Might (+4 to Might TN for 3 rounds)
1x Elixir of True Sight (Cannot be affected by Illusion magic for one encounter)
THE MISSION FORWARD
Esbern: "Our next step is the Throat of the World. We must reach High Hrothgar and convince the Greybeards to let us pass. They guard the path to Paarthurnax. Without their blessing... we'd be climbing through a blizzard against masters of the Voice."
The Path Forward:
Travel to High Hrothgar
Convince the Greybeards to grant passage
Climb to the summit and meet Paarthurnax
Learn what he knows about Dragonrend and the Elder Scroll
Obtain both
Face the impossible choice
Confront Alduin

PHASE 4: HIGH HROTHGAR
Location: The Throat of the World, High Hrothgar Monastery
 NPCs: Master Arngeir, Borri, Wulfgar, Einarth (the Greybeards)
THE SEVEN THOUSAND STEPS
The pilgrimage to High Hrothgar is grueling - a steep climb up a mountain path marked by ancient shrines.
The Journey:
Takes a full day of climbing
Weather worsens as they ascend (cold, wind, eventually blizzard conditions)
Potential encounters: frost trolls, ice wraiths, or just the mountain itself
Esbern's Dialogue During the Climb:
"The Greybeards are masters of the Voice - the Thu'um. They've taken vows of silence, speaking only when absolutely necessary, because their voices are so powerful they could level buildings. Only Master Arngeir speaks regularly - his control is absolute."
"They believe the Voice should only be used for worship of Kynareth, never for violence. They're... pacifists. Warrior-monks who refuse to fight. They're going to be very skeptical of us."
ARRIVING AT HIGH HROTHGAR
READ ALOUD:
"The monastery emerges from the blizzard like a fortress of grey stone. It's built into the mountain itself, solid and ancient. The wind howls, but here, in the courtyard, it's strangely calm.
The doors swing open as you approach. Standing in the entrance is an elderly Nord man in grey robes. His eyes are sharp despite his age, and when he speaks, his voice carries a resonance that makes the air itself vibrate.
'We felt the death of the dragons. We felt the Voice used in anger. You are not dov-ah-kiin - you are not Dragonborn. Yet you come to the Throat of the World. Why?'"
MASTER ARNGEIR
Arngeir is the only Greybeard who speaks freely. The others communicate through him or through the Thu'um itself.
Arngeir's Position:
He knows dragons are returning
He's waiting for the Dragonborn (as prophecy demands)
He's deeply skeptical of mortals trying to use the Voice for violence
He will NOT grant access to Paarthurnax without proof of worthiness
The Initial Conversation:
Arngeir: "You killed Sahloknir and Nahagliiv. You are dragon-slayers. Hunters. But that does not make you worthy to meet the master."
Esbern: "Master Arngeir, with respect, there IS no Dragonborn. We've waited. We've searched. If we wait for prophecy while Alduin devours the worldΓÇö"
Arngeir: (cutting him off) "The prophecy is CLEAR. The Dragonborn will come. They always have. Your impatience changes nothing."
Esbern: "And if you're wrong? If this time, there is no hero? What then?"
Arngeir: (long pause) "Then... we have failed. And the world ends as it was always meant to."
THE TEST OF WORTHINESS
Arngeir will not be argued with easily. He requires PROOF that the party is worthy to climb to the summit.
Arngeir: "If you truly believe you can walk the path meant for the Dragonborn, then prove it. Demonstrate that you understand the Voice, that you can wield it with discipline, not just violence."
The Three Trials:
TRIAL 1: THE SHOUT OF FORCE
Challenge: Learn and demonstrate the first word of Unrelenting Force (Fus)
Arngeir teaches them the word by speaking it, carving it into their mind with the Voice. They must then use it to strike a series of training targets with controlled precision - enough force to hit them, not enough to destroy them.
Mechanics:
Party must make Standard Magic checks to control the Shout
Success: They hit the target cleanly
Failure: Too much force (destroys target) or too little (misses)
They need 3 successes out of 5 attempts (as a group)
Purpose: This shows they can learn the Voice and control it

TRIAL 2: THE WAY OF PEACE
Challenge: Solve a conflict without violence
Arngeir presents a scenario: "Two monks of our order have a dispute. One believes we should aid Skyrim's people directly. The other believes we must remain isolated. They will not speak to each other. Mediate. Find peace."
Mechanics:
This is a social encounter with two stubborn NPCs (Borri and Wulfgar, communicating through writing)
Party must use Guile (Persuasion) to find common ground
Multiple approaches work: compromise, finding shared values, appealing to their vows
Requires at least 2 successful checks from different party members
Purpose: This shows they value peace and wisdom, not just strength

TRIAL 3: THE MEDITATION OF SILENCE
Challenge: Endure the mountain's trial
Arngeir leads them to an outdoor platform exposed to the elements. They must meditate in silence for one hour while the wind and cold batter them.
Mechanics:
Each party member makes a Might Save (Standard TN)
Success: They endure the cold and maintain focus
Failure: They lose focus and must be brought inside (counts against the trial)
At least half the party must succeed
Purpose: This shows they have discipline and endurance, the foundations of the Voice

THE JUDGMENT
If the party passes the trials (at least 2 out of 3):
Arngeir: (with grudging respect) "You have shown discipline. Control. Wisdom beyond what I expected from dragon-slayers. Perhaps... perhaps there is another path. One not written in prophecy, but forged by will."
(He gestures to the doors behind him, which lead up the mountain)
"The path to the summit is yours. Paarthurnax will see you. But know this - he is ancient beyond measure. He will judge you more harshly than I have. And if he finds you unworthy... the mountain will not let you leave."
If they fail the trials:
Arngeir: "You are warriors, yes. But warriors alone cannot walk the path of the Voice. Return when you have learned discipline. Until then, the summit is forbidden."
(The party must leave and return later, or attempt to climb the mountain without permission - which is possible but VERY dangerous)

THE FINAL CLIMB
With Arngeir's blessing, the party can climb the final stretch to the Throat of the World.
The Ascent:
The blizzard intensifies to near-impossible levels
Visibility drops to mere feet
The cold is brutal (party takes 2 Frost Damage per 10 minutes unless protected)
The path is treacherous - one wrong step means a fatal fall
Esbern stays behind - he's too old and frail to make this climb.
Esbern's Farewell: "I'll wait here. This is your journey now. When you meet Paarthurnax, remember - he's a dragon. No matter how wise he seems, he's still a dragon. Be careful."

PHASE 5: THE THROAT OF THE WORLD
Location: The Summit - The highest peak in Skyrim
 NPC: Paarthurnax, the ancient dragon
THE SUMMIT
READ ALOUD:
"The blizzard breaks suddenly as you crest the final ridge. The summit of the Throat of the World is a broad plateau of snow-covered stone, open to a sky so clear and blue it seems unreal.
And perched on the Word Wall at the center, his wings folded, his scales grey-white with age, is the largest dragon you've ever seen.
He's ancient. Scars crisscross his body - wounds from battles fought before your civilization existed. His eyes are amber, bright with intelligence, and when he turns his head to regard you, the movement is slow and deliberate.
When he speaks, his voice is a rumble like distant thunder, but there's no threat in it. Only... curiosity.
'Drem yol lok. Greetings. I have waited long for dov-ah-kiin. But you are not them. You are... dohvora. Dragonslayers. Hunters of my kin.'"
PAARTHURNAX
Paarthurnax is not hostile. He's intrigued.
Paarthurnax: "You killed Sahloknir. Nahagliiv. Both krosiir - brothers - of mine. Both servants of Alduin. Yet you stand here, not to slay me, but to... speak? Kriid. Curious."
(He shifts, his massive body settling on the Word Wall)
"Why have you climbed to the monahven - the mother-wind - if not to fulfill the prophecy? Where is dov-ah-kiin?"
THE CONVERSATION
The party must explain their situation. Paarthurnax will listen, interrupt with questions, and gradually piece together the truth.
Key Points to Cover:
There is no Dragonborn (Paarthurnax is shocked: "Ni dov-ah-kiin? This was not foreseen.")
Alduin is returning, resurrecting dragons (Paarthurnax: "Mu los fin. It has begun.")
They need to learn Dragonrend and find the Elder Scroll (Paarthurnax: "Ah. You seek the path the ancient Nords walked. Brave. Foolish. But brave.")
Paarthurnax's Response:
"You ask much. Dragonrend is not a gift - it is a curse. A Shout born of hatred, of forcing dov to feel rok - mortality. It corrupts those who use it. And you are already mortal. To use it is to weaponize your own death against my kin."
(He pauses, considering)
"But Alduin has returned. He breaks the natural order. He believes he is rah - god. He will devour the world not because it is time, but because he is vey - cruel."
(He looks at them directly)
"I will help you. Not because I believe you can succeed. But because I have spent three thousand years atoning for my own krosis - crimes. I will not let Alduin destroy what I have worked to preserve."
THE OFFER
What Paarthurnax Will Do:
Teach the Way of the Voice:


He will grant each party member ONE Shout word (their choice from: Fus/Ro/Dah for Unrelenting Force, or Feim for Become Ethereal)
He will explain the philosophy: "The Voice is not a weapon. It is a tool of understanding. Use it with kren - thought."
Guide Them to Dragonrend:


"Dragonrend is not written on any wall. It was created by mortals, born of their hatred of dov. To learn it, you must witness its creation."
"You need the Elder Scroll. The same scroll used to banish Alduin. It shows the past, the present, the future. With it, you can witness the moment Dragonrend was first used."
"The Scroll is hidden in a Dwemer ruin - Alftand, beneath Blackreach. The College of Winterhold knows where it lies."
Provide Strategic Knowledge:


"Alduin cannot be killed in Mundus - this world. If you strike him down here, he will simply flee to Sovngarde, the Hall of Valor, and regenerate."
"To kill him permanently, you must follow him to Sovngarde itself. There, cut off from Mundus, he can truly die."
"To reach Sovngarde, you need a portal. Only dragons know how to open them. When the time comes... I will help."
ESBERN'S SUSPICION
If Esbern were present (he's not - he stayed at High Hrothgar), he would be deeply suspicious. When the party returns and reports this conversation:
Esbern: "He's lying. He has to be. Dragons don't help mortals unless there's something in it for them. He's Alduin's brother - what if this is all a trap? What if he's leading you to Sovngarde so Alduin can kill you there?"
The party must decide: Do they trust Paarthurnax? Or Esbern?

PHASE 6: THE ELDER SCROLL QUEST
Trigger: Party agrees to seek the Elder Scroll
 Location: College of Winterhold ΓåÆ Alftand ΓåÆ Blackreach ΓåÆ Tower of Mzark
THE COLLEGE OF WINTERHOLD
The party must travel to the College to learn where the Elder Scroll is hidden.
NPC: Urag gro-Shub (the librarian)
Urag's Information: "An Elder Scroll? You're madder than most of the students here. Those artifacts are beyond mortal comprehension - looking at one can burn out your eyes or shatter your mind. But yes, I know where one is. The Dwemer were obsessed with them. There's a Scroll locked in a mechanism deep beneath Blackreach, in a place called the Tower of Mzark."
The Path:
Travel to Alftand (Dwemer ruin in the northern mountains)
Fight through automated Dwemer defenses (Dwarven Spheres, Spiders, Centurions)
Navigate Blackreach (vast underground cavern, full of Falmer)
Find the Tower of Mzark
Solve the mechanism puzzle to retrieve the Scroll
The Scroll's Effect:
READ ALOUD:
"The Elder Scroll unfurls in your hands, and the world BREAKS.
You're no longer in the tower. You're standing on the Throat of the World, but it's different. The sky is red. Dragons circle overhead. And before you, three ancient Nords in furs and iron stand facing a massive black dragon - Alduin.
One of them steps forward and SHOUTS. The word is not in any language you know, but you feel it in your soul:
'JOOR ZAH FRUL!'
Alduin SCREAMS. He's forced to land, wings crumpling, his immortal body suddenly vulnerable. The Nords attack.
And then you're back in the tower, the Scroll rolled shut in your hands, your head pounding with new knowledge.
You know Dragonrend now. You understand mortality as a weapon."
Game Effect:
All party members learn Dragonrend (Joor Zah Frul)
Cooldown: Once per combat
Effect: Forces one dragon to land and remain grounded for 3 rounds. During this time, the dragon is Vulnerable (all damage against it is increased by +5) as it experiences mortality for the first time.

PHASE 7: THE IMPOSSIBLE CHOICE
Trigger: Party returns to the Throat of the World with Dragonrend
 Location: Summit of the Throat of the World
 NPCs: Paarthurnax, Esbern (who has climbed up to meet them)
THE CONFRONTATION
The party arrives at the summit, ready to finalize their plan to face Alduin. Paarthurnax is pleased they succeeded.
But Esbern has followed them up the mountain. He's exhausted from the climb, shaking with cold and effort, but determined.
Esbern: (breathing hard) "Before you go to face Alduin... there's one more thing that must be done."
(He looks at Paarthurnax)
"The dragon must die."
ESBERN'S ARGUMENT
Esbern: "I know he's helped you. I know he seems wise and peaceful. But he's Alduin's brother. His lieutenant. Three thousand years ago, Paarthurnax ruled mortals as a tyrant. He burned villages. He enslaved nations. Yes, he betrayed Alduin - but only because he saw an opportunity for power."
(He steps forward, his old body trembling but his voice strong)
"What happens when Alduin is dead? Who leads the dragons then? Paarthurnax is the oldest, the strongest. He could take Alduin's place. And we'd have traded one tyrant for another."
"The Blades were founded to protect mortals from dragons. ALL dragons. Even this one. ESPECIALLY this one."
(He looks at the party)
"Kill him now, before we face Alduin. It's the only way to be sure. It's the only way to keep Skyrim safe."
PAARTHURNAX'S RESPONSE
Paarthurnax does not move. He simply watches, calm.
Paarthurnax: "Zu'u lost ni kos. I understand. I am dov. My nature is domination. Pruzah - power. I have fought this nature for three thousand years, but it never leaves. Every day, I choose. Every day, I resist."
(He looks at Esbern)
"You are right to fear me. I am dangerous. But I have proven myself through time. I have taught mortals to resist tyranny. I have guided the Greybeards. I have done no harm."
(He turns to the party)
"But I cannot prove what I will do tomorrow. I can only show what I have done yesterday. If you believe I am too dangerous to live, then strike. I will not resist. I have earned death many times over."
(Pause)
"But know this: I am the last who remembers the Way of the Voice. When I die, that knowledge dies with me. The remaining dragons will have no guide. No teacher. They will return to their nature - conquest and fire. Some may follow the path I showed them. Most will not."
(He settles onto the Word Wall)
"The choice is yours. Security in my death... or hope in my life."
THE THREE PATHS
This is the climax of the Blades questline. The party must choose.

PATH A: KILL PAARTHURNAX
If the party attacks, Paarthurnax does not fight back. He accepts his death.
READ ALOUD:
"Paarthurnax lowers his head, exposing his throat. His ancient eyes close.
'Krosis. I am sorry. For what I was. For what I could become. Zu'u lost ni kos.'
He does not move as the blade strikes. Does not cry out. His death is silent, dignified.
As his body dissolves into ash and light, his soul rises - not to one of you, but into the sky itself, dispersing like morning mist.
Esbern stands there, tears streaming down his face.
'Thank you. You've done the right thing. The hard thing. The Blades will remember this.'"
Immediate Consequences:
Esbern:
Fully committed to the party now
Provides maximum support for the Alduin fight
Will help rebuild the Blades after Alduin's death
Dies content, believing he fulfilled his duty
The Greybeards:
When the party returns to High Hrothgar, Arngeir refuses to speak to them
The doors are barred
A note is left: "You have murdered the master. You are not welcome here. Ever."
All Thu'um training is permanently lost
The Way of the Voice dies with Paarthurnax
Dragons:
With no leader, dragons scatter
Some are hunted down by Skyrim's forces
Others raid and terrorize independently
No unifying philosophy, no path toward peace
Alduin Fight:
No Paarthurnax to provide guidance or support
Party must face Alduin alone
Slightly harder difficulty (no dragon ally, no strategic advice)
Epilogue (After Alduin's Death):
Dragons become a persistent, ongoing threat
They raid holds, attack travelers, burn farms
It's not an apocalypse, but it's a constant war
The reformed Blades spend decades hunting dragons
Skyrim is "safe" but scarred
The party are celebrated as heroes, but at great cost
Esbern dies years later, satisfied his order's mission was completed
The knowledge of the Voice is lost forever

PATH B: SPARE PAARTHURNAX
If the party refuses to kill Paarthurnax:
Esbern: (voice breaking) "Then... then the Blades die here. I am the last. And I will not serve dragon-lovers. I will not betray everything my order stood for."
(He looks at the party with utter devastation)
"You've doomed us all. When he turns - and he WILL turn - remember this moment. Remember that you chose this."
(He turns and begins the climb back down the mountain)
"I'm done. Fight Alduin yourselves. Die yourselves. I want no part of it."
Immediate Consequences:
Esbern:
Leaves permanently
Will not help with the Alduin fight
Party loses access to Blades equipment and support
If Delphine was rescued, she goes with him (loyalty to Esbern)
Both disappear into hiding, bitter and broken
The Greybeards:
Arngeir is grateful when he learns of the decision
"You have shown wisdom beyond your years. The Way of the Voice endures."
Continued access to Thu'um training
The Greybeards will provide support (advice, training, sanctuary)
Paarthurnax:
Deeply grateful
"Zu'u tinvaak hi. I will not forget this trust."
Provides maximum support for Alduin fight
Will join the battle directly at a critical moment
Alduin Fight:
Paarthurnax participates, providing crucial support
He can tank some of Alduin's attacks
He provides tactical advice mid-fight
Slightly easier difficulty
Epilogue (After Alduin's Death):
Paarthurnax assumes leadership of the dragons
He teaches the Way of the Voice to those willing to learn
Some dragons follow - they embrace peace and restraint
Some dragons refuse - they continue raiding and killing
It's a mixed outcome: better than total war, but not perfect peace
Skyrim has dragon allies AND dragon enemies
The Blades are gone forever
Paarthurnax lives on, a constant presence on the Throat of the World
The party must trust that their gamble was worth it

PATH C: CONVINCE ESBERN (Very Hard)
This is the "best" ending, but it requires significant effort.
The Challenge:
The party must convince Esbern that sparing Paarthurnax is the right choice. This requires three Very Hard (-6) Guile (Persuasion) checks, each representing a different argument.
Argument 1: Evidence of Redemption "Paarthurnax has proven himself over three thousand years. He betrayed Alduin when he could have ruled beside him. He taught mortals the Thu'um, giving them the power to resist. He's had countless opportunities to return to tyranny, and he hasn't. That's not luck - that's choice."
Esbern's Counter: "Three thousand years of waiting. Waiting for the right moment. He's patient. Dragons are immortal - what's three millennia when you're planning to rule forever?"
Success: Esbern hesitates. "I... I suppose that's true. But..."

Argument 2: Practical Necessity "We NEED him. Not just for Alduin - for after. You said it yourself: dragons will return to their nature without guidance. Paarthurnax is the only one who can lead them toward peace. If we kill him, we guarantee a dragon war. If we spare him, we have a chance at something better."
Esbern's Counter: "And if that 'something better' is just a different kind of tyranny? What if he leads the dragons to conquer Skyrim more efficiently?"
Success: Esbern looks uncertain. "That... that could happen. But you're right. Without him, it's guaranteed war. With him... there's a chance."

Argument 3: Evolution of the Blades "The Blades' purpose was to serve and protect. For thousands of years, you served the Dragonborn Emperors. But there is no Dragonborn. There is no Empire. The world has changed. The Blades must change too. Not dragon-slayers - dragon-wardens. Watching. Mediating. Preventing wars before they start. That's how your order survives."
Esbern's Counter: "The Blades are dragon-slayers. It's what we ARE. If we're not that... what are we?"
Success: Esbern goes quiet for a long time. He looks at the mountains, at Paarthurnax, at his own shaking hands.

THE DECISION
If the party succeeds on at least two out of three checks:
Esbern: (voice hoarse) "Perhaps... perhaps you're right. Perhaps I've been so focused on what the Blades were that I couldn't see what they could become."
(He looks at Paarthurnax)
"We were dragon-slayers. Hunters. Protectors through violence. But in a world where dragons return... perhaps we must be something else. Wardens. Mediators. Preventing the wars before they burn the world."
(He turns back to the party)
"I will spare you, dragon. But I will watch you. Always. If you falter - if you return to your nature - I will know. And I will act."
Paarthurnax: "That is... acceptable. Zu'u los ni oblaan. I am not eternal. But while I live, I will guide my kin toward the Voice, not the flame. And you, last of the Blades... you may watch. It is your right."
Immediate Consequences:
Esbern:
Agrees to the "New Blades" philosophy
Remains with the party
Provides full support for Alduin fight
Will help rebuild the Blades as dragon-wardens after Alduin's death
Dies years later with hope, not bitterness
The Greybeards:
Grateful and impressed
Continued support and training
Arngeir: "You have shown wisdom that even we did not expect."
Paarthurnax:
Maximum trust and gratitude
Full support in Alduin fight
Will join the battle at the most critical moment
Provides ongoing guidance post-Alduin
Alduin Fight:
Both Esbern and Paarthurnax support the party
Easiest version of the fight
Combined Blades tactics and dragon knowledge
Epilogue (After Alduin's Death):
BEST OUTCOME: Paarthurnax leads willing dragons toward peace
The "New Blades" hunt rogue dragons and protect peaceful ones
Not perfect - some dragons still raid, some mortals still fear them
But genuine coexistence begins
Esbern rebuilds the Blades with a new purpose
The Way of the Voice endures
Skyrim is safer than it's been in millennia
The party created something new from the ashes of the old

PHASE 8: ALDUIN (The Final Battle)
Trigger: The Paarthurnax choice is resolved
 Location: Sovngarde (the Nordic afterlife)
OPENING THE PORTAL
With Dragonrend learned and the choice made, the party is ready to face Alduin.
The Problem: Alduin cannot be permanently killed in Mundus (the mortal world). If struck down here, he'll simply flee to Sovngarde and regenerate.
The Solution: They must follow him to Sovngarde and kill him there.
How to Open the Portal:
Paarthurnax (if alive) or ancient Blades texts (if not) reveal the method:
A dragon's shout can tear open a portal to Sovngarde
The portal requires a specific location: the Throat of the World (where the barrier between worlds is thinnest)
They must lure Alduin there and weaken him enough to flee
THE TRAP
The Plan:
Call Alduin to the Throat of the World (use the Clear Skies shout to break his storm)
Weaken him with Dragonrend (force him to land and fight)
Deal enough damage that he flees to Sovngarde
Follow him through the portal (with Paarthurnax's help to open/hold it)
Kill him permanently in the Hall of Valor
The First Fight (Throat of the World):
Alduin arrives in fury:
READ ALOUD:
"The sky darkens. Storm clouds gather, red and black, swirling with unnatural fury. And through the clouds descends a dragon larger than any you've faced.
Alduin is MASSIVE. His scales are black as midnight, edged with blood-red. His eyes burn with an ancient, terrible intelligence. When he roars, the mountain itself trembles.
'SAHROT THUR QAHNAARIN! Arrogant mortal insects! You dare stand where the Dovahkiin should stand? You dare challenge the World-Eater with stolen knowledge?'
He lands on the Word Wall with earth-shaking force.
'ZU'U UNSLAAD! I AM ETERNAL! I cannot be slain! This world is MINE to devour!'"
Combat Notes:
Alduin is a Legendary Tier Boss (adjust stats for party level)
He uses multiple Thu'um: Fire Breath, Meteor Storm, Fear
Dragonrend is essential - it forces him to land and makes him Vulnerable
Goal: Reduce him to 25% HP, then he flees
When Alduin Flees:
READ ALOUD:
"Alduin SCREAMS in rage and pain. His massive wings beat once, twice, lifting him into the air.
'NIVAHRIIN MORAH! Cowards who hide behind mortality! You have not won! I am eternal! I will return to Sovngarde and heal! And when I return, I will BURN THIS WORLD TO ASH!'
He tears through the sky, and reality RIPS. A portal of swirling light and shadow opens in the air above the Throat of the World - a gateway to the afterlife itself."
Paarthurnax (if alive): "The portal will not stay open long! I will hold it! Go! ZOK WUTH MAAR! Kill him in the Hall of Valor! End this!"
Esbern (if present): "This is it! Everything we've worked for! Don't let him escape! GO!"
SOVNGARDE
READ ALOUD:
"You step through the portal and emerge in a land of mist and eternal twilight. The sky is a swirling aurora of green and purple. The ground is stone, ancient and weathered, carved with runes.
Before you stretches a massive bridge made of whale bone, leading to a distant hall. The Hall of Valor - Shor's domain, where Nord heroes feast and fight for eternity.
But the path is blocked by mist - thick, poisonous, unnatural. This is Alduin's doing. He's feeding on the souls of the dead, growing stronger.
You can hear his voice echoing through the mist:
'This is MY realm now! The souls of Sovngarde will fuel my return! You cannot stop me here!'"
The Challenge:
The party must:
Use Clear Skies shout to part the mist (learned from Paarthurnax or the Greybeards)
Cross the bridge while fighting spectral enemies (Alduin's thralls)
Enter the Hall of Valor
Recruit three ancient Nord heroes to help fight Alduin
Face Alduin in the final battle
The Three Heroes:
Gormlaith Golden-Hilt (Warrior)
Hakon One-Eye (Archer)
Felldir the Old (Mage)
These are the same Nords who banished Alduin originally using the Elder Scroll.
Their Support:
They know Dragonrend (can help force Alduin to land)
They provide flanking support
They distract Alduin, giving the party openings
THE FINAL BATTLE
READ ALOUD:
"Alduin emerges from the mist at the center of Sovngarde, perched on a massive stone platform. He's healed, but he's also trapped - there's nowhere left to run.
'So. You have come to my domain. Here, I am STRONGEST. Here, the souls of warriors fuel my power. Here, you will DIE.'
The three ancient heroes step forward beside you.
Gormlaith raises her blade: 'For Skyrim!' Hakon draws his bow: 'For the living!' Felldir raises his staff: 'For the future!'
And the final battle begins."
Combat:
Alduin at full power (Legendary Boss, adjusted for party tier + 3 NPC allies)
Must use Dragonrend repeatedly to keep him grounded
The three heroes will fall one by one, leaving the party to finish him
When reduced to 0 HP, Alduin dies PERMANENTLY
Alduin's Death:
READ ALOUD:
"Alduin crashes to the ground, his massive body shuddering. Black blood pours from his wounds. He tries to rise, tries to shout, but no sound comes.
For the first time in existence, the World-Eater understands mortality.
'Zu'u... unslaad... I am... eternal...'
His body begins to crack. Light pours from the fissures - not the light of a dragon soul ascending, but something else. Something breaking apart.
The World-Eater dissolves into ash and light, and for the first time in thousands of years, Sovngarde is silent.
The three heroes stand at your side, watching.
Gormlaith: 'It is done. The prophecy is fulfilled... not by the one foretold, but by those who stood when no hero came.'
Felldir: 'You have done what we could not. You have ended the World-Eater's reign forever.'
Hakon: 'The living may rest easy. And we... we may finally do the same.'"
The Return:
The portal opens again. The party can return to Mundus.
When they emerge on the Throat of the World:
Paarthurnax (if alive) is waiting: "Alduin is no more. The dragons are free. What they do with that freedom... time will tell."
Esbern (if present) collapses in exhausted relief: "We did it. Against all odds. We actually did it."
The Greybeards (if friendly) emerge from High Hrothgar and bow: "The prophecy is fulfilled by will, not by fate. You have our respect."

